{"title_page": "Garreth Roberts", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2016}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Garreth Roberts\n| image                = \n| fullname             =\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1960|11|15|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Kingston upon Hull|Hull]], England\n| height               = {{height|ft=5|in=6}}\n| position             = [[Midfielder]]\n| years1               = 1978\u20131991\n| clubs1               = [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hullcity-mad.co.uk/feat/edy5/garreth_roberts_27820/index.shtml|title=Garreth Roberts|date=24 June 2008|work=Hull City Online|accessdate=12 June 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| caps1         = 409 | goals1 = 47\n}}\n'''Garreth Roberts''' (born 15 November 1960) is an English retired professional [[association football|footballer]] who spent his whole career with hometown club [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]], including captaining them to two promotions.\n\n==Education==\n\nRoberts was educated at [[Wolfreton School]].\n\n==Career==\nRoberts made his debut against [[Bury F.C.|Bury]] in March 1979, coming on as a substitute for the injured [[Alan Warboys]].<ref name=\"CityMag1109\">{{cite journal|date=November 2009|title=Garreth Roberts' A to Z|journal=City Magazine|publisher=Hull City A.F.C.|issue= 51|pages=20\u201324<!--|accessdate=16 November 2009-->}}</ref> He was made Captain of the team in his early twenties.<ref name=\"CityMag1109\" /> He played primarily in [[midfielder|midfield]], although in the later stages of his career he was also deployed in defence as a [[full-back (association football)|full-back]] or [[sweeper (association football)|sweeper]].<ref name=\"CityMag1109\" />\n\nRoberts was forced to retire from professional football at the age of 31 due to injuries.<ref name=\"CityMag1109\" /> His testimonial match saw Hull-born [[Nick Barmby]] make his debut for [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] and score two goals against his hometown club.<ref name=\"CityMag1109\" />\n\nRoberts was voted 17th in a list of the top 100 Hull City players compiled for the club's centenary.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hullcityafc.net/page/NewsDetail/0,,10338~640167,00.html|title=The Top 100 Tigers|date=15 March 2005|publisher=Hull City A.F.C.|accessdate=12 June 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120415160432/http://www.hullcityafc.net/page/NewsDetail/0%2C%2C10338~640167%2C00.html|archivedate=15 April 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of one-club men in association football|One-club man]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Roberts, Garreth}}\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Kingston upon Hull]]\n[[Category:Footballers from the East Riding of Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:Hull City A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Association football utility players]]\n[[Category:People educated at Wolfreton School]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2016}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Garreth Roberts\n| image                = \n| fullname             =\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1960|11|15|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Kingston upon Hull|Hull]], England\n| height               = {{height|ft=5|in=6}}\n| position             = [[Midfielder]]\n| years1               = 1978\u20131991\n| clubs1               = [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hullcity-mad.co.uk/feat/edy5/garreth_roberts_27820/index.shtml|title=Garreth Roberts|date=24 June 2008|work=Hull City Online|accessdate=12 June 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| caps1         = 409 | goals1 = 47\n}}\n'''Garreth Roberts''' (born 15 November 1960) is an English retired professional [[association football|footballer]] who spent his whole career with hometown club [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]], including captaining them to two promotions.\n\n==Education==\n\nRoberts was educated at [[Wolfreton School]].\n\n==Career==\nRoberts made his debut against [[Bury F.C.|Bury]] in March 1979, coming on as a substitute for the injured [[Alan Warboys]].<ref name=\"CityMag1109\">{{cite journal|date=November 2009|title=Garreth Roberts' A to Z|journal=City Magazine|publisher=Hull City A.F.C.|issue= 51|pages=pp.&nbsp;20\u201324<!--|accessdate=16 November 2009-->}}</ref> He was made Captain of the team in his early twenties.<ref name=\"CityMag1109\" /> He played primarily in [[midfielder|midfield]], although in the later stages of his career he was also deployed in defence as a [[full-back (association football)|full-back]] or [[sweeper (association football)|sweeper]].<ref name=\"CityMag1109\" />\n\nRoberts was forced to retire from professional football at the age of 31 due to injuries.<ref name=\"CityMag1109\" /> His testimonial match saw Hull-born [[Nick Barmby]] make his debut for [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] and score two goals against his hometown club.<ref name=\"CityMag1109\" />\n\nRoberts was voted 17th in a list of the top 100 Hull City players compiled for the club's centenary.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hullcityafc.net/page/NewsDetail/0,,10338~640167,00.html|title=The Top 100 Tigers|date=15 March 2005|publisher=Hull City A.F.C.|accessdate=12 June 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120415160432/http://www.hullcityafc.net/page/NewsDetail/0%2C%2C10338~640167%2C00.html|archivedate=15 April 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of one-club men in association football|One-club man]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Roberts, Garreth}}\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Kingston upon Hull]]\n[[Category:Footballers from the East Riding of Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:Hull City A.